node.text:
Transformed from a former railroad corridor, the Polly Ann Trail extends north from Oakland County’s Orion Township for a total of 16.9 miles. With connections to the Paint Creek Trail and access to parks and public spaces in several communities, residents and visitors alike enjoy exploring the trail’s diverse terrain and scenery. Two paved sections are great for cyclists and are accessible to trail users of all levels of mobility, while more rural sections are perfect for those seeking a respite into nature.
 
Pure Michigan Trails is a video series that explores Michigan’s diverse trail network. Whether it’s hiking, biking or paddling, each episode navigates a different trail to share the activities and amenities that await. Click the link in our bio to learn more!

node.text:
Step off the hiking trail and hop into a kayak as we explore Antrim County's Chain of Lakes Water Trail.
 
This flatwater system is a paddler's paradise, made from 12 lakes and interconnected rivers in the northwest corner of Michigan's lower peninsula. With highly visible signage and 84 access sites - including many barrier free access points, your adventure on the Chain of Lakes' 100+ miles of water trail can be as long or short as you want. See why this diverse and unique natural resource is just the beginning of your northern Michigan experience in our newest episode of Pure Michigan Trails.
 
Pure Michigan Trails is a video series that explores Michigan’s diverse trail network. Whether it’s hiking, biking or paddling, each episode navigates a different trail to share the activities and amenities that await. Click the link in our bio to learn more.

Freshwater sand dunes, towering bluffs, pristine beaches and expansive views are among the many things that make Sleeping Bear Dunes National Lakeshore a popular destination for outdoor enthusiasts in all seasons of the year.
 
In the first of our Pure Michigan Trails video series, we explore the Sleeping Bear Heritage Trail, a 21-mile pathway that connects visitors to the Lakeshore with the neighboring communities of Empire and Glen Arbor, along with the popular attractions and hidden gems found throughout the park.
 

 
Discover more Pure Michigan Trails at michigan.org/PureMichiganTrails

A longtime favorite of local skiers and riders, Traverse City's @mtholiday is a true community ski area.
 
While winter fun is always on the agenda during the snowy season, Mt. Holiday is also a gathering place for locals and visitors alike, with a friendly atmosphere to make you feel right at home. Ride along as our guide Otie explores Upper Holiday and Northwind, and feel the thrills and chills of snow tubing under the lights.
 
We'll explore a new ski area each week as we #SkiPureMichigan all winter long. Visit the link in our bio to discover more signature runs at ski areas across #PureMIchigan.

Transformed from a former railroad corridor, the Polly Ann Trail extends north from Oakland County’s Orion Township for a total of 16.9 miles. With connections to the Paint Creek Trail and access to parks and public spaces in several communities, residents and visitors alike enjoy exploring the trail’s diverse terrain and scenery. Two paved sections are great for cyclists and are accessible to trail users of all levels of mobility, while more rural sections are perfect for those seeking a respite into nature.
 
Pure Michigan Trails is a video series that explores Michigan’s diverse trail network. Whether it’s hiking, biking or paddling, each episode navigates a different trail to share the activities and amenities that await. Click the link in our bio to learn more!

Today is #NationalLighthouseDay! With 3,200 miles of #GreatLakes shoreline and some of the nation's most active waterways, it's no surprise that Michigan has more lighthouses than any state in the country, providing guidance to any who travel by water and marking history through the generations. 

If you live in Michigan, you can help restore and preserve Michigan's lighthouses by purchasing a "Save our Lights" license plate for your vehicle. Each plate helps provide the revenue needed to ensure that Michigan's lighthouses have a bright future. To learn more, click the link in our bio and select "Save our Lights".
